eu.brengard.businesscalendar.entitites

Class BusinessDay

  • java.lang.Object
    • eu.brengard.businesscalendar.entitites.BusinessDay
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class BusinessDay
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    A business day, defined by a day-of-week and "working" time slots.

    This class provides methods to create and handle a business day. This includes a method to get the Duration getDuration two LocalTimes by counting only the time where the company is open.

    A business day is constituted of two objects :

    • A DayOfWeek which is the day-of-week for that business day.
    • A collection of BusinessTimeSlot defining the business day time slots. It is important to know that defining two time slots crossing (eg: 9h - 12h , 10h - 12h) will result in a pondered duration on the crossing times. (eg: if we take again the two time slots 9h - 12h , 10h - 12h ; the duration getDuration 11h and 12h using getDuration(LocalTime, LocalTime) method will return 2 hours.
    Since:
    1.8
    Author:
    Nicolas BRENGARD (eu.brengard.businesscalendar.entitites@brengard.eu)
    See Also:

      • getDuration

        public java.time.Duration getDuration(java.time.LocalTime startInclusive,
                                      java.time.LocalTime endExclusive)
        Get the duration getDuration two localTimes. This duration is calculated from "working hours" (eg: Duration = real Duration - day-of-week off hours Duration). It is important to know that if this business day contains two time slots crossing (eg: 9h - 12h , 10h - 12h) this method will return a pondered duration on the crossing times. (eg: if we take again the two time slots 9h - 12h , 10h - 12h ; the duration getDuration 11h and 12h will be 2 hours.
        Parameters:
        startInclusive - the start instant, inclusive, not null.
        endExclusive - the end instant, exclusive, not null.
        Returns:
        the duration getDuration two localTimes, not null, eventually pondered, eventually negative.
